    <exercise number="15.1.1">
      <p>
        Compute the Riemann sum <m>S_{4,3}</m> to estimate the double integral of <m>f(x,y) = xy</m> over <m>\c{R} = [1,3] \times [1,2.5]</m>. 
        Use the regular partition and upper-right vertices of the sub-rectangles as sample points. 
      </p>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="15.1.9">
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\ds \iint_\c{R} (15 - 3x)\, dA</m>, where <m>\c{R} = [0,5] \times [0,3]</m>, and sketch the corresponding solid region. 
      </p>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="15.1.11">
      <p>
        The following table gives the approximate height at quarter-meter intervals of a mound of gravel. 
        Estimate the volume of the mound by computing the average of the two Riemann sums <m>S_{4,3}</m> with lower-left and upper-right vertices of the sub-rectangles as sample points. 
      </p>

      <image source="sec151_HW11_Diagram.png" width="50%"></image>
    </exercise>

    <exercise number="15.1.17">
      <p>
        Use symmetry to evaluate the double integral 
        <md>
          \iint_\c{R} \sin(x)\, dA\, , \qquad \c{R} = [0,2\pi] \times [0,2\pi]
        </md>
        
      </p>
    </exercise>

    <exercisegroup>
    
